{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2eacd598-c10e-4699-86fd-3a4b2723bde5","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n### Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`. On macOS you can rely on the OS-level crash reporting:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain stack traces and register state.\n\n3. **Use `lldb` to capture a core** — attach before or after the crash:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) process save-core core.dump\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `/cores/` directory** — if core dumps are enabled (`ulimit -c unlimited`) and `/cores/` exists with write permissions, macOS writes core files there:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp -c /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\nThe Apple `.ips` crash reports (step 2) are often the quickest path since they're generated automatically with no prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d1553044-bc0a-4f62-96be-e7f5ee76d241","outputTokens":361},"id":"db86f749-7e14-417c-99e3-3527a38ed22a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:57:09.470Z","parentId":"c2bb6225-1ba8-4453-a609-2726abe1c4ee"}
